<h1 class="hero-h">Gym business plan <em style="color:#00C853;font-style:italic;">for 2026.</em></h1>
<p class="hero-sub">A working gym business plan template plus a worked example for a 2,500 sq ft boutique studio. Built for first-time owners pitching for SBA financing, franchise applications, or investor capital — and built to reflect what 2026 fitness operations actually look like, including the AI-native operational model that materially changes the financials.</p>
</div></div>

<div style="background:#0A1A0A;border-top:1px solid #1A3A1A;border-bottom:1px solid #1A3A1A;padding:1.25rem 2.5rem;">
<div style="max-width:880px;margin:0 auto;display:flex;justify-content:space-between;align-items:center;gap:1rem;flex-wrap:wrap;font-size:0.78rem;color:#8FAF8F;">
<div>By <a href="/about" style="color:#F0FFF0;text-decoration:none;font-weight:500;">Bill Colbert</a> · <span style="color:#4A6A4A;">Founder, Treetop Growth Strategy</span></div>
<div style="color:#4A6A4A;">Published May 2026 · <a href="/content-library" style="color:#8FAF8F;text-decoration:none;">More from the library</a></div>
</div>
</div>

<section><div class="sec-inner"><span class="lbl">What a 2026 gym business plan needs to include</span><h2 class="h2">The standard sections — updated</h2><p class="body">A bank, SBA lender, franchisor reviewer, or investor expects your business plan to cover the standard sections — executive summary, market analysis, services, marketing plan, operations, management, financial projections. Below are the sections, the contemporary 2026 framing for each, and where most first-time owners get it wrong.</p><div class="callout"><p><strong>The single biggest 2026 difference</strong> from older gym business plan templates: the operational model section. AI-native operations (where AI agents handle lead nurture, member onboarding, retention monitoring) materially reduce the Year-1 staff line item — often by \$40K-\$80K per location. Lenders and investors who see this modeled correctly are meaningfully more comfortable with first-year projections.</p></div></div></section>
<section><div class="sec-inner"><span class="lbl">Section 1</span><h2 class="h2">Executive summary</h2><p class="body">One page. Most lenders read this and skim the rest. It should cover:</p><ul class="ul"><li>Concept (what kind of gym, what makes it differentiated)</li><li>Location and target market (1 sentence)</li><li>Total capital required and use of funds (specific)</li><li>Revenue model and pricing</li><li>Year-1, Year-2, Year-3 revenue and net income projections</li><li>Owner's background and why-this-team-can-execute</li></ul></div></section>
<section><div class="sec-inner"><span class="lbl">Section 2</span><h2 class="h2">Market analysis</h2><ul class="ul"><li><strong>Local market sizing</strong> — total addressable members in your trade area (drive-time radius). Use census data, fitness participation rates (typically 20-25% of adults are gym members).</li><li><strong>Competitive landscape</strong> — list every gym in a 3-mile radius. Document price points, formats, gaps.</li><li><strong>Target member persona</strong> — specific. Age, household income, schedule, fitness goals.</li><li><strong>Why this market needs another gym</strong> — gap analysis. What format/price point/experience isn't currently served well.</li></ul></div></section>
<section><div class="sec-inner"><span class="lbl">Section 3</span><h2 class="h2">Concept and services</h2><ul class="ul"><li>Format (boutique, full-service, CrossFit, PT studio, etc.)</li><li>Specific class types and schedule structure</li><li>Membership tiers and pricing</li><li>Optional services (PT, nutrition, recovery, retail)</li><li>Member experience differentiators (the why-them-vs-competitors)</li></ul></div></section>
<section><div class="sec-inner"><span class="lbl">Section 4</span><h2 class="h2">Marketing plan</h2><p class="body">This is where most first-time owner business plans are weakest. Be specific:</p><ul class="ul"><li>Pre-launch marketing budget and tactics (paid ads, local partnerships, founding-member offers)</li><li>Ongoing acquisition channel mix and projected CAC</li><li>Member retention plan (AI-driven retention monitoring is the 2026 standard — see <a href="/how-to-use-ai-for-gym-member-retention" style="color:#00C853;">how to use AI for gym member retention</a>)</li><li>Referral program structure</li><li>Local community engagement</li></ul></div></section>
<section><div class="sec-inner"><span class="lbl">Section 5</span><h2 class="h2">Operations</h2><h3 class="h3">The AI-native operational model</h3><p class="body">This is the single most important update to a 2026 gym business plan. The traditional staffing model (2 front-desk + 1 GM + instructor pool) is no longer required for boutique-and-below formats. AI agent platforms purpose-built for fitness (<a href="https://fitagentic.ai" style="color:#00C853;">fitagentic.ai</a> is the most-deployed) handle lead nurture, new-member onboarding, retention monitoring, and member-facing coaching — work that historically required 1-2 W-2 staff per location.</p><h3 class="h3">What to document</h3><ul class="ul"><li>Hours of operation</li><li>Staffing plan (lean AI-native vs hybrid vs traditional; show the cost comparison)</li><li>Technology stack (gym CRM + AI agent platform + payment processing)</li><li>Supplier relationships (equipment, cleaning, music licensing)</li><li>Standard operating procedures (member intake, class booking, billing)</li><li>Quality control measures</li></ul></div></section>
<section><div class="sec-inner"><span class="lbl">Section 6</span><h2 class="h2">Management team</h2><ul class="ul"><li>Owner-operator background — relevant experience, certifications</li><li>Coach team — head coach if hired, instructor pool plan</li><li>Advisor relationships if any (mentor, accountant, attorney)</li><li>Why this team can execute (specific evidence, not aspirational)</li></ul></div></section>
<section><div class="sec-inner"><span class="lbl">Section 7</span><h2 class="h2">Financial projections</h2><p class="body">The longest and most-scrutinized section. Must include:</p><ul class="ul"><li><strong>Startup cost breakdown</strong> — use our <a href="/cost-to-start-a-gym" style="color:#00C853;">cost-to-start-a-gym guide</a> and the <a href="/gym-startup-budget-template" style="color:#00C853;">140-line budget template</a></li><li><strong>Use of funds table</strong> — specific category breakdowns</li><li><strong>Revenue projections</strong> — month-by-month for Year 1, quarterly for Years 2-3. Realistic member ramp.</li><li><strong>Operating expense projections</strong> — month-by-month for Year 1</li><li><strong>Cash flow projections</strong> — showing when breakeven is achieved</li><li><strong>Sensitivity analysis</strong> — what if member ramp is 25% slower than plan</li><li><strong>Funding request</strong> — total ask, equity vs debt split</li></ul><div class="callout"><p><strong>Where most first-time plans fail SBA review:</strong> over-optimistic member ramp + under-budgeted working capital. Plan for breakeven at month 9-15, not month 4-6.</p></div></div></section>
<section><div class="sec-inner"><span class="lbl">Worked example</span><h2 class="h2">1,800 sq ft boutique HIIT studio, Tier 2 metro</h2><h3 class="h3">Capital requirements</h3><ul class="ul"><li>Facility (lease + buildout): \$110K</li><li>Equipment: \$45K</li><li>Licensing + insurance: \$15K</li><li>Software (Year 1): \$8K</li><li>Marketing + launch: \$25K</li><li>Working capital (6 mo): \$60K</li><li><strong>Total: \$263K</strong></li></ul><h3 class="h3">Revenue model</h3><ul class="ul"><li>Membership tiers: \$149/mo (4 classes), \$199/mo (8 classes), \$249/mo (unlimited)</li><li>Average revenue per member: \$185/mo</li><li>Member capacity: 350 at full ramp</li></ul><h3 class="h3">3-year projections (AI-native operational model)</h3><div class="table-wrap"><table class="t"><thead><tr><th>Metric</th><th>Year 1</th><th>Year 2</th><th>Year 3</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Members (year-end)</td><td>120</td><td>240</td><td>310</td></tr><tr><td>Annual revenue</td><td>\$185K</td><td>\$510K</td><td>\$680K</td></tr><tr><td>Annual operating costs</td><td>\$215K</td><td>\$310K</td><td>\$390K</td></tr><tr><td>Net (before owner draw)</td><td>-\$30K</td><td>\$200K</td><td>\$290K</td></tr><tr><td>Cumulative cash position (incl funding)</td><td>+\$70K</td><td>+\$270K</td><td>+\$560K</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p class="body"><strong>Funding ask:</strong> \$263K, structured as 25% owner equity (\$66K) + 75% SBA 7(a) loan (\$197K).</p><p class="body"><strong>Contrast with traditional staffing model:</strong> Year-1 operating costs would be \$265K-\$285K instead of \$215K, pushing breakeven 6-9 months later and reducing the funding ask viability.</p></div></section>
<section><div class="sec-inner"><span class="lbl">SBA-specific considerations</span><h2 class="h2">If applying for SBA financing</h2><ul class="ul"><li><strong>7(a) loan max:</strong> \$5M for working capital + equipment + real estate. Most gym loans are \$150K-\$1.2M.</li><li><strong>504 loan:</strong> for real estate purchases (if you're buying vs leasing). 10% down, 40% SBA debenture, 50% bank loan.</li><li><strong>Personal guarantee:</strong> standard. Personal credit score should be 680+; 720+ is comfortable.</li><li><strong>Owner equity injection:</strong> SBA typically requires 10-20% owner cash equity in the project.</li><li><strong>Industry-specific guidance:</strong> NAICS code 713940 (Fitness and Recreational Sports Centers). Some SBA lenders specialize in fitness/franchise lending.</li></ul></div></section>
<section><div class="sec-inner"><span class="lbl">Common business plan mistakes</span><h2 class="h2">What gets plans rejected</h2><ul class="ul"><li><strong>Generic / template-looking executive summary.</strong> Lender skips the rest.</li><li><strong>Over-optimistic member ramp.</strong> Aggressive growth assumptions don't survive scrutiny.</li><li><strong>Under-budgeted working capital.</strong> The #1 cause of gym failure; lenders know this.</li><li><strong>Vague marketing plan.</strong> "We'll do social media" doesn't cut it. Specific channels, budgets, CAC assumptions.</li><li><strong>No competitive analysis.</strong> Saying "there's no competition" is a red flag.</li><li><strong>Ignoring the AI-native operational option.</strong> 2026 lenders increasingly understand this; modeling traditional-only staffing reads as out-of-touch.</li><li><strong>Owner-can-do-everything fantasy.</strong> Plan for time off, illness, scaling beyond owner-as-everything.</li></ul></div></section>
<section><div class="sec-inner"><span class="lbl">Companion tools</span><h2 class="h2">What to use with this template</h2><ul class="ul"><li><a href="/cost-to-start-a-gym" style="color:#00C853;">Cost to start a gym</a> — definitive line-item breakdown</li><li><a href="/gym-startup-cost-calculator" style="color:#00C853;">Gym startup cost calculator</a> — interactive estimator</li><li><a href="/gym-startup-budget-template" style="color:#00C853;">Gym startup budget template</a> — 140-line categorized budget</li><li><a href="/from-coach-to-studio-owner-ai-native-playbook" style="color:#00C853;">From coach to studio owner playbook</a> — for trainers writing their first business plan</li><li><a href="/personal-trainer-business-plan" style="color:#00C853;">Personal trainer business plan</a> — for PT studio specifically</li></ul></div></section>

